# Creating a function to clean the text
def Clean(Text):
    sms = re.sub('[^a-zA-Z], ,', ' ', str(Text)) 
    sms = sms.replace("/",",")
    sms = sms.split()
    sms = ' '.join(sms)
    return sms
bgg["Mechanics"] = bgg["Mechanics"].apply(Clean)
bgg["Domains"] = bgg["Domains"].apply(Clean)

Out[31]:
<Axes: >

Rating Average & Complexity Average have a moderately positive correlation, so we will take a closer look at

those two. Several other features have weak correlations with Rating Average, so we will include them in a later Random Forest model to see how their combined influence may be used to predict the Rating Average of a new game.

Also, the BGG Rank and Rating Average have a strong, negative correlation. This makes sense when looking at our earlier plots where as the Rating Average increases our BGG Rank will decrease as it trends towards a number 1 rank.

Owned Users and Users Rated have a strong correlation since typically people who purchase a game are more likely to take the time to review it. In addition, Complexity Average has a minor, positive correlation with Play Time and Min Age as games that tend to go for longer play times and are for older players will most likely have a higher levell of complexity to their game designs.

Linear Regression Model Using Complexity & Rating Average

In[35]:
# Setting up the x and y variables for a linear regression model on how accurately Complexity Average can be 
#  used to predict Raing Average
X = bgg2['Complexity Average'].values.reshape(-1,1)
y = bgg2['Rating Average'].values.reshape(-1,1)
In[36]:
# Setting up the train-test-split for the model
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
In[37]:
# Initializing the model
regressor = LinearRegression()  

# Training the algorithm
regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)

Meaning that at 0 for complexity average, our model predicts a rating average of 5.35 and for each single point

increase in complexity average, our rating average can be predicted to rise by 0.53.

In[42]:
# Looking at the metrics values on our model to see its accuracy. A good model will have errors trending 
# closer to 0 and an R^2 score trending closer to 1

print('Mean Absolute Error:', metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))  
print('Mean Squared Error:', metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))  
print('Root Mean Squared Error:', np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
print('R^2 Score:', metrics.r2_score(y_test, y_pred))

Mean Absolute Error: 0.6271243481764985
Mean Squared Error: 0.6601674404295852
Root Mean Squared Error: 0.8125068863890232
R^2 Score: 0.24410413791119123

All of the error scores are relatively high and our R_squared value is realtively low. We want values closer to 0.0 for our errors and closer to 1.0 for our coefficient of determination. This means that we can determine that our model is perhaps not too accurate, but not wildly inaccurate either. This makes sense since complexity average and rating average have some correlation, but are not enough to determine a solid predictability on how to aim for a specific rating average score based solely off of the complexity level of a game. It seems that our model can explain about 24% of the data's variance, a rather small amount.

Mechanics & Domains

We will now take a closer look at the Mechanics and Domains columns from our cleaned dataframe to explore their insights and to use them in conjunction with our other columns within a random forest regression model to observe how they may influence predictions on Rating Average.

The following functions were taken from Karnika Kapoor's Board Game Analysis notebook on Kaggle, and used to extract the entries within the Mechanics and Domains columns for further analysis.

https://www.kaggle.com/code/karnikakapoor/board-games-analysis#DATA-PREPROCESSING

In[47]:
# Code to get Corpus
def Get_Corpus(bla):
    corpus= []
    for i in bla:
        item = i.split(",")
        corpus += item
    return corpus

# Code to delete extra space
def space_eleminator(list):
    vals=[]
    for i in list:
        m = i.lstrip()
        vals.append(m)
    return vals

Mechanics_corpus = space_eleminator(Get_Corpus(bgg["Mechanics"]))
Domains_corpus = space_eleminator(Get_Corpus(bgg["Domains"]))

Data Preprocessing of Mechanics & Domains

In[52]:
# Using One Hot Encoding to prepare data for a random forest regression model.

# Creating dummy variables for Mechanics
Mech_df = bgg["Mechanics"].str.get_dummies(",")

# To avoid dummy variable trap
Mech_df = Mech_df.drop('Not Mentioned', axis= 1)

# Creating dummy variables for Domains
Dom_df = bgg["Domains"].str.get_dummies(",")

# To avoid dummy variable trap
Dom_df = Dom_df.drop('Not Mentioned', axis= 1)
In[53]:
# Concatenating our One Hot Encoded dataframes to our earlier dataframe for use in the model
bgg_rf = pd.concat([bgg2, Mech_df, Dom_df], axis=1)

bgg_rf.dropna(inplace=True)

All of our scores are considerably good and close to what we would like to see in an accurate model. This, however, is a problem. Our model should NOT be this accurate based off of what we know from our earlier explorations of the data. We know that most features only have a weak or moderate correlation with the Ranking Average scores, so our model should not be scoring this well. What could be causing this?

In[64]:
# Creating a feature importance graph to see which aspects of our data are influencing the model the most.

# Setting up the features
features = X_train.columns
importances = rf.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)

# Customized number 
num_features = 20 

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.title('Feature Importances')

# Only plot the customized number of features
plt.barh(range(num_features), importances[indices[-num_features:]], color='b', align='center')
plt.yticks(range(num_features), [features[i] for i in indices[-num_features:]])
plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
plt.show()

It seems that our model is overwhelmingly being influenced by the BGG Rank column from our dataset. This now makes sense for why our evaluation scores were so good and the model able to accurately predict the Rating Average values. A games BGG Rank is a direct result of averaging the ratings that users have given it. If a game has a higher BGG Rank, then of course it will have a larger Rating Average and it becomes rather simplistic for the model to predict values based off of this information. This, however, does not help us to gain any insights on which features may lead to a higher Rating Average score BEFORE a game is released. So we must adjust our model once again to remove BGG Rank from the features and re-run everything.

# Looking at a feature importance plot to see how things have changed.

# Setting up the features
features2 = X2_train.columns
importances2 = rf2.feature_importances_
indices2 = np.argsort(importances2)

num_features2 = 20 

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.title('Feature Importances')

# Only plot the customized number of features
plt.barh(range(num_features2), importances2[indices2[-num_features2:]], color='b', align='center')
plt.yticks(range(num_features2), [features2[i] for i in indices2[-num_features2:]])
plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
plt.show()

Complexity Average is now the most important feature influencing our model, which matches up with what we know from our correlation matrix heatmap. Surprisingly, Year Published is the second most influential feature. This could possibly be explained by the fact that board games have been seeing a growing interest and consumer base over the last 10 - 15 years (most recent game is from 2022) and people who are invested in board games as a hobby are more likely to play newer games and to subsequently review and rate them. This leads to more recent games having some influence in our model. Following this we have the same expected features from our earlier insights; Users Rated, Owned Users, Play Time, Max Users, and Min Age all have some impact on our model.

Conclusions

  • The feature most associated with a higher Rating Average score was Complexity Average.
  • However, it only has a moderate correlation with increasing Rating Average. Alone it is not a defining feature, but ensuring the game has some amount of complexity can lead to a higher rating average.
  • The next most important features were the Year Published, the Users Rated, and the Owned Users. These had small impacts on the Rating Average, but can also be simply explained by the increasing popularity of board games as a hobby leading to more reviews and higher averages.
  • Our Random Forest Regression model had a Mean Squared Error of 0.40474 and an R2 Score of 0.55403 which are moderately accurate in predicting a Rating Average score based off our data and what we expected to see based off of our correlation heatmap.
  • There were 195 unique Mechanics and 8 unique Domains (genres), but none of them had a significant impact on predicting Rating Average scores.
  • With no particular feature heavily influencing our Rating Average, the developers have the freedom to play with its features however they want without being concerned over how it may impact the game's rating score.
